WEBVTT

00:01.434 --> 00:04.003
Antecedently on Fargo...

00:05.539 --> 00:06.540
Hmm?

00:08.842 --> 00:10.511
Take Irish.

00:10.544 --> 00:11.545
Merda.

00:11.578 --> 00:14.314
‐(gunshots)
‐(tires screech)

00:14.347 --> 00:15.549
(horn honking)

00:15.582 --> 00:18.318
If you ordered it, I got no
problem accepting consequence.

00:18.351 --> 00:19.720
But I know
you don't want to start a war.

00:19.753 --> 00:21.487
I didn't order a goddamn hit!

00:23.590 --> 00:25.526
LOY:
Who's calling the shots
over there?

00:25.559 --> 00:28.161
The ape or the pipsqueak?

00:29.496 --> 00:31.264
You're giving orders now?

00:32.432 --> 00:33.734
Are we at war?

00:33.767 --> 00:35.201
Not yet.

00:35.235 --> 00:37.170
(screaming)

00:37.203 --> 00:38.705
But we're trying real hard.

00:38.739 --> 00:40.073
GAETANO:
These mulignani‐‐

00:40.106 --> 00:42.208
they think that...

00:42.242 --> 00:43.610
we are weak.

00:43.644 --> 00:45.078
They're right.

00:45.111 --> 00:46.312
You're weak.

00:46.346 --> 00:47.814
You took a shot.

00:47.848 --> 00:49.215
You missed.

00:49.249 --> 00:51.184
Now my enemy's got 300 guns.

00:53.353 --> 00:54.521
What is it with everybody today,

00:54.555 --> 00:55.789
thinking
they can talk back to me

00:55.822 --> 00:56.790
like we're having a debate?

00:56.823 --> 00:57.791
You,

00:57.824 --> 00:59.325
put the muscle on Cannon.

00:59.359 --> 01:01.327
Bust some heads,
make some arrests.

01:01.361 --> 01:02.863
LOY:
Sell 200 to Mort Kellerman.

01:02.896 --> 01:05.632
Tell him
he can have 'em at cost.

01:05.666 --> 01:07.467
But he owes us devotion.

01:08.902 --> 01:11.137
(whooping)

01:11.171 --> 01:13.740
(applause, whistling)

01:16.577 --> 01:19.112
(playing "Moanin'")

01:47.541 --> 01:49.876
♪ ♪

02:17.971 --> 02:20.473
♪ ♪

02:24.711 --> 02:26.947
Man, that cat can blow.

02:26.980 --> 02:27.948
(door opens)

02:27.981 --> 02:29.482
Party's over!

02:29.516 --> 02:30.951
(woman screams)

02:30.984 --> 02:32.285
The party's over!

02:32.318 --> 02:34.187
We got to go!

02:36.757 --> 02:38.324
Freeze, Sambo.

02:38.358 --> 02:40.193
(grunting)

02:42.696 --> 02:43.697
(grunting continues)

02:48.001 --> 02:49.503
Stop! You're killing him!

02:49.536 --> 02:50.671
(grunting)

02:50.704 --> 02:52.739
(panting)

02:52.773 --> 02:54.474
‐(grunts)
‐(wheezes)

02:54.508 --> 02:56.943
♪ ♪

03:01.347 --> 03:02.348
(officer chuckles)

03:15.796 --> 03:17.798
(siren wailing)

03:20.901 --> 03:22.903
‐(car doors close)
‐(indistinct chatter)

03:25.506 --> 03:27.273
Hai visto.

03:27.307 --> 03:29.643
That's how it's done.

03:34.581 --> 03:37.851
(indistinct chatter)

03:39.586 --> 03:41.522
(car doors close)

03:42.723 --> 03:45.258
‐(engine starts)
‐I really hate that guy.

03:48.495 --> 03:50.831
♪ ♪

04:03.376 --> 04:06.680
Rifle Claus came early
this year.

04:06.713 --> 04:08.549
Something like that.

04:08.582 --> 04:10.551
You know the terms.

04:10.584 --> 04:12.719
Guns for loyalty.

04:12.753 --> 04:15.455
We going to war
with the Eyeties?

04:15.488 --> 04:17.524
Depends.

04:17.558 --> 04:19.692
On?

04:20.961 --> 04:22.996
(engine starts)

04:25.666 --> 04:26.900
Arrivederci!

04:26.933 --> 04:28.835
DOCTOR SENATOR:
Just stay by the phone!

04:28.869 --> 04:30.871
We'll call you when we need you!

04:40.113 --> 04:41.615
(thunder rumbling)

04:41.648 --> 04:43.517
(blows)

04:50.857 --> 04:52.826
What do you want to do
about the funeral home?

04:52.859 --> 04:55.028
It's ours now.

04:55.061 --> 04:57.764
Tell 'em. Make it clear.

04:57.798 --> 05:00.333
If they tell us where the dykes
are, we'll let 'em live.

05:00.366 --> 05:01.467
If not...

05:01.502 --> 05:02.503
‐MAN: Police!
‐(door opens)

05:03.136 --> 05:04.771
(shouting)

05:04.805 --> 05:05.806
(grunts)

05:06.840 --> 05:08.642
(grunting)

05:08.675 --> 05:10.443
‐Cracker‐ass motherfucker.
‐The fuck you say?

05:10.476 --> 05:11.712
(exclaims)

05:11.745 --> 05:13.580
ODIS:
Grab some air.

05:13.614 --> 05:14.948
Hey.

05:14.981 --> 05:16.917
I said grab some air!

05:18.118 --> 05:19.620
You boys are breaking the law.

05:19.653 --> 05:21.955
What law?

05:21.988 --> 05:23.824
Having too many teeth.

05:23.857 --> 05:25.859
(hisses)

05:29.596 --> 05:30.864
Whoops.

05:32.398 --> 05:34.367
What's my money bag doing here
on the floor?

05:35.168 --> 05:37.671
Better put this back in the car.

05:37.704 --> 05:39.372
I know you.

05:40.173 --> 05:42.643
No, you don't.

05:42.676 --> 05:43.844
(crash)

05:43.877 --> 05:45.612
LOY:
Yeah.

05:46.780 --> 05:50.551
I heard about you.

05:50.584 --> 05:51.752
(crash)

05:51.785 --> 05:54.688
Odis here was in the war.

05:54.721 --> 05:56.590
Minesweeper.

05:56.623 --> 06:00.494
Every day, take his men...

06:00.527 --> 06:03.096
and hoof it on ahead
of the army,

06:03.129 --> 06:05.131
looking for land mines.

06:06.166 --> 06:08.434
You shut up.

06:10.436 --> 06:13.006
Lot of turnover in Odis's unit.

06:13.039 --> 06:15.141
Boom! There goes Sammy.

06:15.175 --> 06:18.144
Boom! There goes Mike.

06:18.178 --> 06:21.748
Whole thing started to make
Odis a little twitchy.

06:21.782 --> 06:23.550
Until, one day,

06:23.584 --> 06:25.552
he couldn't take it no more.

06:25.586 --> 06:28.188
So he laid down in the grass.

06:28.221 --> 06:31.424
Just looks at the clouds.

06:33.627 --> 06:36.129
Army rolls up.

06:36.162 --> 06:38.198
Colonel says,

06:38.231 --> 06:39.800
"Odis,

06:39.833 --> 06:42.068
did you clear this field?"

06:42.102 --> 06:44.470
And Odis says,

06:44.505 --> 06:47.073
‐"Yes, sir."
‐(gasping)

06:47.107 --> 06:48.609
‐See...
‐I cleared it.

06:48.642 --> 06:50.210
Colonel had to take a piss.

06:50.243 --> 06:53.446
So he walks out into the field
and...

06:55.749 --> 06:56.950
Boom!

06:59.185 --> 07:02.455
They got to send him home
in a tureen.

07:06.059 --> 07:08.795
That's a pot they put soup in.

07:11.965 --> 07:14.234
(hoarsely):
Get 'em out of here.

07:14.267 --> 07:16.236
Not‐not him.

07:16.269 --> 07:18.238
OFFICER:
Get 'em all out. Go.

07:18.271 --> 07:19.806
OFFICER 2:
You heard him.

07:25.178 --> 07:27.648
(stammers, exhales)

07:29.683 --> 07:32.052
You didn't fight in the war,
did you?

07:32.085 --> 07:34.721
‐(panting)
‐Nah, man.

07:34.755 --> 07:38.091
Why would I fight for a country
that wants me dead?

07:39.626 --> 07:41.061
(chuckles)
Boom!

07:41.094 --> 07:42.563
(shuddering)

07:45.999 --> 07:47.701
Josto Fadda says...

07:47.734 --> 07:50.203
stick to the deal.

07:53.907 --> 07:54.908
Boom!

07:59.580 --> 08:01.915
♪ ♪

08:23.236 --> 08:25.739
‐(man groaning)
‐(phone ringing in distance)

08:35.015 --> 08:37.551
(groaning continues)

08:51.064 --> 08:53.567
(groaning loudly)

08:55.769 --> 08:58.271
Shh!

08:58.304 --> 09:02.008
ETHELRIDA:
Dear Dr. Harvard...

09:05.679 --> 09:09.082
I am writing
to inform you of the actions

09:09.115 --> 09:10.751
of one of your nurses.

09:10.784 --> 09:12.018
(knocking)

09:12.052 --> 09:13.186
(door opens)

09:13.219 --> 09:14.621
THURMAN:
Decent?

09:18.191 --> 09:19.626
Lights out.

09:19.660 --> 09:21.628
Big day tomorrow.

09:21.662 --> 09:23.129
What?

09:23.163 --> 09:24.297
Your birthday.

09:25.331 --> 09:26.700
Don't tell me you forgot.

09:26.733 --> 09:28.234
(exhales)
Yeah.

09:28.268 --> 09:31.037
Right, it's a‐‐ it's a big day.

09:31.071 --> 09:34.374
Hey, Dad, what‐what's laudanum?

09:34.407 --> 09:36.610
Chemistry homework?

09:37.644 --> 09:39.680
Not exactly.

09:41.047 --> 09:42.015
Well, let's see.

09:42.048 --> 09:43.283
Laudanum, it's a...

09:43.316 --> 09:45.085
it's a painkiller.

09:45.118 --> 09:46.152
Real potent.

09:46.186 --> 09:47.988
Is it dangerous?

09:48.989 --> 09:50.356
Could be if you take too much.

09:50.390 --> 09:51.892
Why?

09:51.925 --> 09:55.395
I saw it at Mrs. Mayflower's,
across the way.

09:55.428 --> 09:57.297
Tons.

09:58.899 --> 10:00.834
Well, hon, she is a nurse.

10:02.235 --> 10:03.837
But it's not something
she should be keeping

10:03.870 --> 10:05.338
around the house.

10:05.371 --> 10:07.407
Lights out now, okay?

10:07.440 --> 10:09.910
Okay, Daddy.

10:13.113 --> 10:14.114
Dad.

10:16.082 --> 10:19.152
Are we ever gonna see
Aunt Zelmare again?

10:21.287 --> 10:23.256
Of course we will.

10:23.289 --> 10:25.391
She's just, you know,

10:25.425 --> 10:28.061
an escaped convict, so...

10:28.094 --> 10:29.696
Where did she go?

10:29.730 --> 10:31.297
(inhales)

10:31.331 --> 10:33.433
She's, um...
(exhales)

10:33.466 --> 10:36.402
Well, I don't know that you need
to know that, young lady.

10:40.340 --> 10:43.043
She's at a residential hotel
downtown, holed up.

10:43.076 --> 10:46.112
The New Parie or some such.

10:46.146 --> 10:49.282
But don't you even think of
going down there, you hear me?

10:51.818 --> 10:53.954
(whispers):
Okay.

10:59.760 --> 11:01.327
Listen...

11:01.361 --> 11:03.129
this Miss Mayflower.

11:03.163 --> 11:05.065
She's...

11:05.098 --> 11:07.200
She's not really...

11:07.233 --> 11:10.003
I mean,
I'm sure she's real nice,

11:10.036 --> 11:12.873
but she's not someone
you should be hanging around.

11:12.906 --> 11:14.941
Huh?

11:14.975 --> 11:18.011
We got a real precarious
situation here,

11:18.044 --> 11:20.747
living outside the law and all.

11:20.781 --> 11:22.415
So...

11:22.448 --> 11:24.751
Not to mention,
I think she might've poisoned

11:24.785 --> 11:26.352
that pie she baked us.

11:26.386 --> 11:28.021
Anyway,

11:28.054 --> 11:30.423
steer clear.

11:30.456 --> 11:31.958
All right.

11:31.992 --> 11:34.995
Say hello to the sandman,
birthday girl.

11:56.382 --> 11:59.986
ETHELRIDA:
I've worked alongside
Oraetta Mayflower

12:00.020 --> 12:01.988
for many years now...

12:02.022 --> 12:03.790
‐(groaning)
‐(thud)

12:03.824 --> 12:07.894
...and felt that I should bring
certain actions of hers

12:07.928 --> 12:10.230
to your attention.

12:10.263 --> 12:13.266
In the last year,

12:13.299 --> 12:15.435
many of Nurse Mayflower's
patients have died

12:15.468 --> 12:18.104
under mysterious circumstances.

12:44.565 --> 12:46.266
NEWSMAN (over radio):
President Truman,
asking Congress

12:46.299 --> 12:48.234
for strong anti‐inflation laws,
says

12:48.268 --> 12:51.271
we must remain strong at home
to beat worldwide communism.

12:51.304 --> 12:53.173
TRUMAN:
And the way to do it is

12:53.206 --> 12:54.508
to have
an anti‐inflation program,

12:54.541 --> 12:56.510
including price controls,

12:56.543 --> 12:59.479
wage controls, rent controls,
credit controls‐‐

12:59.513 --> 13:01.481
controls that really

13:01.515 --> 13:03.984
hold down prices
and the cost of living.

13:04.017 --> 13:06.286
You carry the five,
don't forget.

13:06.319 --> 13:09.055
(Josto sighs)

13:09.089 --> 13:10.924
What's he working on?

13:10.957 --> 13:14.495
Satchel, tell the boss
what you're working on.

13:14.528 --> 13:16.162
Long division.

13:16.196 --> 13:19.232
You're teaching him?

13:19.265 --> 13:22.068
‐I'm bad at math.
‐Funny.

13:22.102 --> 13:24.337
No one ever says
"I'm bad at English."

13:24.370 --> 13:27.173
What?

13:27.207 --> 13:28.809
Nothing.

13:30.443 --> 13:33.847
We got 'em on the run, I think,
after last night.

13:33.880 --> 13:36.583
The way I figure,
he'll go home...

13:36.617 --> 13:38.619
Gaetano.

13:38.652 --> 13:41.588
This thing's rightly sorted,
there's no war to fight.

13:41.622 --> 13:43.824
He'll go home.

13:45.125 --> 13:47.127
Would you?

13:48.294 --> 13:51.097
Would I what?

13:51.131 --> 13:54.134
Italy's over.
We turned it into a toilet.

13:54.167 --> 13:57.070
This is the land of plenty.

13:57.103 --> 13:59.072
Boom times.

13:59.105 --> 14:01.107
Would you go back?

14:03.610 --> 14:06.112
Maybe he gets
another city, then.

14:06.146 --> 14:08.048
Cleveland.

14:08.081 --> 14:10.050
Yeah, Moreno's in Cleveland.

14:10.083 --> 14:12.285
No, you watch.

14:12.318 --> 14:15.488
Train's gonna pull in next week,
maybe earlier‐‐

14:15.522 --> 14:18.058
ten, 20 guys
from the old country.

14:18.091 --> 14:21.628
"I just thought we could use
the help," he'll say,

14:21.662 --> 14:23.864
your brother,
but make no mistake.

14:25.231 --> 14:27.901
Those are his men...

14:27.934 --> 14:30.036
and they're here to take over.

14:30.070 --> 14:32.506
So what do we do?

14:33.674 --> 14:35.676
Making me say it

14:35.709 --> 14:38.478
instead of you isn't gonna make
doing it any easier.

14:48.221 --> 14:50.524
Plenty of people are bad
at English.

14:50.557 --> 14:53.393
Yeah, but they're not proud
of it.

14:53.426 --> 14:56.329
This problem you got‐‐
it's a math problem.

14:56.362 --> 14:58.532
Either you divide them,

14:58.565 --> 15:01.935
or they multiply.

15:01.968 --> 15:03.970
Capisce?

15:06.339 --> 15:08.341
I got to piss.

15:17.417 --> 15:19.285
Be ready.

15:21.722 --> 15:23.990
When the shooting starts,

15:24.024 --> 15:26.560
we vanish.

15:50.684 --> 15:53.419
(indistinct whispering)

15:53.453 --> 15:55.455
(clattering)

16:05.065 --> 16:07.067
(whispers):
It's the niece.

16:17.243 --> 16:18.679
Show her the whistle.

16:18.712 --> 16:20.581
(whistles two notes)

16:20.614 --> 16:22.749
So we know
you're friendly next time.

16:22.783 --> 16:24.751
Hey, you got any food on you?

16:24.785 --> 16:27.153
There's too much heat
in the street to go out,

16:27.187 --> 16:29.355
and we ate all the saltines
last night.

16:29.389 --> 16:32.392
(sighs)
I got some pretzels in my bag.

16:35.428 --> 16:36.797
You want a drink?

16:36.830 --> 16:38.431
We're drinking.

16:38.464 --> 16:40.300
No, ma'am.

16:40.333 --> 16:42.769
Come on now. It's your birthday.

16:42.803 --> 16:44.705
You're grown.

16:44.738 --> 16:47.073
(laughs)
What, you thought I forgot?

16:47.107 --> 16:49.576
Shit, I wish I could be
with y'all to celebrate,

16:49.610 --> 16:51.144
eat me some cake.

16:51.177 --> 16:53.780
‐Cake?
‐But this gonna have to do.

16:53.814 --> 16:56.583
Oh, well,
liquor clouds the mind.

16:56.617 --> 16:58.251
That's what I'm counting on.

16:58.284 --> 17:00.353
(Ethelrida laughs)

17:03.189 --> 17:05.157
To my beautiful niece

17:05.191 --> 17:07.594
and another twirl
around the sun.

17:07.627 --> 17:09.029
I'll slurp to that.

17:12.833 --> 17:15.035
‐(Swanee exhales)
‐(Zelmare clears throat)

17:16.737 --> 17:18.338
Aunt Zelmare,

17:18.371 --> 17:21.307
what would you do
if you saw something wrong?

17:21.340 --> 17:23.710
Something you could fix?

17:23.743 --> 17:25.712
Nothing.

17:25.746 --> 17:27.513
What do you mean?

17:27.548 --> 17:29.750
I mean nothing.

17:29.783 --> 17:31.585
'Cause you're a criminal?

17:31.618 --> 17:33.353
I ain't a criminal.

17:34.387 --> 17:35.856
You're innocent you're saying?

17:35.889 --> 17:38.324
Girl, I ain't been innocent
since Uncle Charlie cornered me

17:38.358 --> 17:40.093
in the shed when I was nine.

17:40.126 --> 17:42.496
Then I don't understand.

17:42.529 --> 17:44.297
SWANEE:
She's saying we ain't criminals.

17:44.330 --> 17:46.132
We're outlaws.

17:46.166 --> 17:48.434
See, criminals play the game.

17:48.468 --> 17:50.103
What game?

17:50.136 --> 17:51.772
Life. The earth.

17:51.805 --> 17:53.473
ZELMARE:
Society, right?

17:53.507 --> 17:54.808
They got their rules.

17:54.841 --> 17:57.343
Banking and family.

17:57.377 --> 18:00.614
An honest dollar
for an honest day's work.

18:00.647 --> 18:02.849
Politics and voting.

18:02.883 --> 18:05.351
And the criminal‐‐
he on the other side of that,

18:05.385 --> 18:07.253
but still he play the game.

18:07.287 --> 18:08.822
And if he plays it long enough,

18:08.855 --> 18:11.224
he even starts
to talk about going legit.

18:11.257 --> 18:12.659
The outlaw, on the other hand...

18:12.693 --> 18:14.327
The outlaw,
on the other hand‐‐

18:14.360 --> 18:18.231
well, we reject the game.

18:18.264 --> 18:20.366
Society.

18:21.702 --> 18:24.370
Ain't nothing organized
about our crime,

18:24.404 --> 18:27.674
'cause our crime is freedom.

18:27.708 --> 18:29.475
No rules.

18:29.510 --> 18:31.277
ZELMARE:
And nothing's ever broke,

18:31.311 --> 18:34.280
and there ain't nothing to fix.

18:34.314 --> 18:36.850
All we want is to live
while we're alive

18:36.883 --> 18:40.554
and... die with a gun
in our hands.

18:42.288 --> 18:44.625
You a bit of an outlaw.

18:44.658 --> 18:46.326
‐Me?
‐Yeah.

18:46.359 --> 18:48.428
Your mama sees it, too.

18:48.461 --> 18:50.697
In the eyes.

18:50.731 --> 18:52.365
That's why she say, "Keep away."

18:52.398 --> 18:55.235
I'm not an outlaw.

18:55.268 --> 18:56.937
Then, which are you‐‐

18:56.970 --> 18:59.239
a convict or a square?

18:59.272 --> 19:02.308
I'm not either one
of those things.

19:02.342 --> 19:03.777
What are you, then?

19:09.282 --> 19:11.317
I'm Ethelrida Pearl Smutny.

19:13.319 --> 19:15.321
One of a kind.

19:25.465 --> 19:27.501
‐Mm‐hmm.
‐What?

19:28.602 --> 19:30.637
What's wrong with her?

19:31.905 --> 19:33.674
Where you off to?

19:33.707 --> 19:35.441
They arrested your son.

19:35.475 --> 19:37.210
I know. I'm handling it.

19:37.243 --> 19:38.712
The same way
you're handling your other son,

19:38.745 --> 19:40.280
lives in an attic
with an Irishman?

19:40.313 --> 19:41.882
Come on now.
We talked about that.

19:41.915 --> 19:45.318
We did, and there he is, eating
someone else's food still.

19:45.351 --> 19:46.687
NARCISSA:
Mm‐hmm.

19:46.720 --> 19:48.589
Doc's gonna bail the boy out
this morning.

19:48.622 --> 19:51.525
He got his bell rung
pretty good, but he's all right.

19:52.659 --> 19:54.227
I'll get him.

19:54.260 --> 19:55.696
He's not the only boy
I got in there.

19:55.729 --> 19:56.963
They all need bailing out.

19:56.997 --> 19:59.633
Now, Doc's gonna sort it.

19:59.666 --> 20:01.735
You best get out of my way.

